description:
Mission Chinese Food is indisputably one of the weirdest restaurants in this part of town. Think Asian, divey, casual, and eccentric. The interior has bright red lighting, a Chinese dragon hanging from the ceiling, and a life-sized Michael Jordan cardboard cutout. Personally, I think that a Fathead of Yao Ming or Manny Pacquiao would have been more fitting. Heck, even Tiger Woods.

They serve Americanized Oriental food, but bear in mind that a good number of dishes are prepared with authentic spices. Having said that, it might not be ideal for the untrained palate. 

// Mongolian Longbeans ($14) - 2 stars
These greens were way too drenched in chili oil.

// Filipino Garlic Fried Chicken ($20) - 3 stars
Although I give them props for providing hot pepper vinegar as the dipping sauce, the chicken itself hardly put a smile on this Filipino boy's face. Jollibee Chicken Joy is better.

// Classic Chow Mein - Beef ($16) - 3 stars
Your average Joe's bowl of beef chow mein.

// Thrice Cooked Bacon & Rice Cakes ($16) - 4 stars
The rice cakes were perfectly chewy, and the bacon had a nice smokey flavor.

// Tingly Pork Mapo Tofu ($15) - 4 stars
I love the numbing sensation that Sichuan peppercorn leaves in the mouth, but it's certainly an acquired taste. True enough, my friends had mixed reviews on this dish, but I enjoyed it.

// Taiwanese Eggplant ($13) - 2 stars
I have a soft spot in my heart for eggplant dishes, but surprisingly, I wasn't a fan of this one. It was too firm and felt under-cooked.

// Salt Cod Fried Rice ($13) - 3 stars
i know the name of this dish literally has "salt" in it, but I wasn't expecting it to be that salty. It also has "cod" in it and definitely could have used more cod.

The food here is so variable, you really have to know what you're ordering or you'll either have a terrific meal or a horrible one.  Here's the ratings:
- Black vinegar peanuts with smoked garlic, anise, fennel are a 4 when you're eating the peanuts on top and then a 1 toward the bottom for the peanuts that are just sitting in the vinegar;
- Sliced peanut noodles in peanut sauce, cheung fun, sweet tofu skin, pickled mustard greens, chives sound good but still just a 3 in flavor;  
- Thrice Cooked Bacon with shanghainese rice cakes, bitter melon, tofu skin, chili oil is so ridiculously spicy hot that you just can't enjoy it and I really like hot food and think that I have a high tolerance for really spicy heat; nevertheless, if it's too hot to enjoy that makes it an automatic 1
-  Red Braised Pork Belly is slow-cooked belly with broccoli, sesame, chickpeas and is the best dish, hands down a 5, and so good I actually ordered a second dish.

This time ordered:
1. pork belly - yum - pork is lean for belly, egg is medium-cooked;
2. ma po tofu - reminded me of dishes I had in Szechuan - almost a soup with earthy, savory flavors, numbing Szechuan peppers;
3. taiwanese eggplant - excellent

All very good.  Best Chinese in the area.
